<h1>The Vinocaster</h1>

<p><img alt="Vinocaster, April 2011" src="images2/original/vinocaster_2011-04-01.jpg"
width="410" height="1000" align="right" /></p>

<p>These pages describe how I built an electric guitar, the body of which was
made from wood salvaged from an old Italian wine vat (<em>tino</em>). I bought
the neck &amp; hardware, I don't really have the skills or equipment for those
bits...yet. </p>

<p>The guitar is working and being used, though I've not finished tweaking (any significant changes and I'll update here). I've also started putting together an effects unit customised to this instrument, <a
href="../vinotone/index.html">Vinotone</a>.</p>

<p>[PS. 2010-02-27 : I've since redone the finish with linseed oil and beeswax,
<a
href="http://www.flickr.com/search/?q=vinocaster&amp;w=51035815526%40N01">some
recent photos on Flickr</a>]</p>

<p>
Construction was in two phases. In the first phase I got the instrument
together and essentially working, but without final shaping and surface
finishing. In the second phase, with the benefit of a few months playing the
guitar, I did the final shaping of the body along with minor modifications and
the surface finishing.<br />

<h2>Contents</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Introduction (this page)
    <ul>
       <li><a href="#background">Background</a></li>
    </ul>
